## DSA Minesweeper

**The problem**
For a Data Structures & Algorithms course project, my team wanted to build something that used real DSA concepts under the hood instead of just implementing them in isolation for an assignment. We wanted something you could actually play, where the structures were doing real work.

**What I did**
We rebuilt classic Minesweeper in C++ with a full DSA backbone: a 2D array for the grid, mines, and cell values; a queue running BFS to reveal large connected empty zones in a single click; a linked list to dynamically store mine positions; a min/max heap for smart mine placement depending on difficulty; and BFS-based graph traversal to make zero-cell reveals fast. The GUI was built with SFML to handle the visuals and input while the data structures did the actual work behind the scenes. I built this with my teammates Syed Ali Turab, Rao Zain Ali, and Fizza Rashid.

**What came of it**
A playable, fully working Minesweeper where every core mechanic (reveal, placement, difficulty scaling) is backed by a specific data structure or algorithm rather than shortcuts, which made it a solid way to actually see DSA concepts working in something real instead of just on paper.

